{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9f1f86dc-dbb2-4657-828c-87ff99c09eef","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** – downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you need after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** – re-installs the *same* versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted/missing files but won't pull newer packages that match the updated SDK.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still see errors, check that the required workload (`maui`) is actually installed:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload list\n```\n\nIf missing, install it explicitly:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"65062f25-f64c-4a3d-ac33-f01bf0f3f244","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` for fixing build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question that doesn't require any tool usage - I can answer it directly.","outputTokens":242,"requestId":"D44B:29787D:1CD6C90:206763A:6A07C13B"},"id":"cc9bd186-8b01-4d05-91a6-75c79b375da0","timestamp":"2026-05-16T00:58:41.624Z","parentId":"5623dd33-a106-41de-87de-03731fb6f4ab"}
